<subSubSection pageId="186" pageNumber="187" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="186" pageNumber="187">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="186" pageNumber="187">
Villous perennial to 40 cm. Leaves sessile, 1.3-7 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
0.4-1.2 cm, oblong to oblanceolate, acute, margin entire, attenuate at the base, softly white-villous. Flowers in dense axillary heads; peduncles 1.5-3.5 cm, exceeding bracts; bracteoles 6-15 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
1-2 mm, linear-lanceolate, acuminate, densely villous; outer sepals 7-10 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
2-3 mm, lanceolate, acuminate, inner sepals narrower, 1-2 mm wide; corolla 2-2.5 cm, unlobed, midpetaline bands pubescent, terminating in a tooth; ovary and style glabrous; style divided c. 3 mm above base, the stigmas 5 mm, longer than the united part of the style. [
<bibRefCitation author="Sa'ad, F" journalOrPublisher="Bronder Offset, Rotterdam" pageId="210" pageNumber="211" pagination="1 - 287" refId="B314" refString="Sa'ad, F, 1967. The Convolvulus species of the Canary Isles, the Mediterranean region, and the Near and Middle East. Mededelingen van het Botanisch Museum en Herbarium van de Rijksuniversite Utrecht. Bronder Offset, Rotterdam: 1 - 287" title="The Convolvulus species of the Canary Isles, the Mediterranean region, and the Near and Middle East. Mededelingen van het Botanisch Museum en Herbarium van de Rijksuniversite Utrecht" year="1967">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Sa’ad">Sa'ad</normalizedToken>
1967
</bibRefCitation>
: 169; 
<bibRefCitation author="Boulos, L" journalOrPublisher="Flora of Egypt" pageId="200" pageNumber="201" pagination="242 - 267" refId="B59" refString="Boulos, L, 2000. . Flora of Egypt 2: 242 - 267" volume="2" year="2000">Boulos 2000</bibRefCitation>
: 247]
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="186" pageNumber="187" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="186" pageNumber="187">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="186" pageNumber="187">
Egypt: Sinai (
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="186" pageNumber="187">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Bové">Bove</normalizedToken>
</emphasis>
503, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="186" pageNumber="187">Danin</emphasis>
s.n. [28/5/1962]), Jordan: Wadi Sirhan (
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="186" pageNumber="187">Hunting Survey</emphasis>
117a). Apparently very rare.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="186" pageNumber="187" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="186" pageNumber="187">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="186" pageNumber="187">
Differs from the two previous species in the pedunculate heads but superficially identical to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="J. R. I. Wood &amp; R. W. Scotland" authorityYear="2015" baseAuthorityName="Wood &amp; Williams &amp; Mitchell &amp; Carine &amp; Harris &amp; Scotland" baseAuthorityYear="2015" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus cephalopodus subsp. bushiricus" order="Solanales" pageId="186" pageNumber="187" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="subSpecies" species="cephalopodus" subSpecies="bushiricus">Convolvulus cephalopodus subsp. bushiricus</taxonomicName>
, from which it is distinguished by the glabrous ovary. Very similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Boiss., Diagn. Pl. Orient. 11: 81. 1849. (Boissier" authorityYear="1849" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus schimperi" order="Solanales" pageId="186" pageNumber="187" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="schimperi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="186" pageNumber="187">Convolvulus schimperi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differing in the ascending habit and in the leaves which are not undulate.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="186" pageNumber="187">The lectotype is a meagre specimen and all the other cited specimens represent more complete material.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
